"Hishida M., Fumizawa M., Inaba Y., Aritomi M., Nomura S., Kosaka S., Yamada S., Ogata K.","Nuclear energy conversion systems for arresting global warming",1997,"Energy Conversion and Management","38","13-10",,"1365","1375",,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0040569206&partnerID=40&md5=7c7d8ffc8ff5d98157f65fd3ee276f84","Japan Atom. Ener. Research Institute, Tokai-mura, Naka-gun, Ibaraki-ken 319-11, Japan; Tokyo Institute of Technology, Ohokayama, Meguro-ku, Tokyo-to 152, Japan; Mitsubishi Heavy Industries Ltd., Akunoura-cho, Nagasaki-shi Nagasaki-ken, 850-91, Japan; Chiyoda Corporation Ltd., Tsurumichuou, Tsurumi-ku, Yokohama-shi, Kanagawa-ken, 230, Japan","Hishida, M., Japan Atom. Ener. Research Institute, Tokai-mura, Naka-gun, Ibaraki-ken 319-11, Japan; Fumizawa, M., Japan Atom. Ener. Research Institute, Tokai-mura, Naka-gun, Ibaraki-ken 319-11, Japan; Inaba, Y., Japan Atom. Ener. Research Institute, Tokai-mura, Naka-gun, Ibaraki-ken 319-11, Japan; Aritomi, M., Tokyo Institute of Technology, Ohokayama, Meguro-ku, Tokyo-to 152, Japan; Nomura, S., Mitsubishi Heavy Industries Ltd., Akunoura-cho, Nagasaki-shi Nagasaki-ken, 850-91, Japan; Kosaka, S., Chiyoda Corporation Ltd., Tsurumichuou, Tsurumi-ku, Yokohama-shi, Kanagawa-ken, 230, Japan; Yamada, S., Mitsubishi Heavy Industries Ltd., Akunoura-cho, Nagasaki-shi Nagasaki-ken, 850-91, Japan; Ogata, K., Mitsubishi Heavy Industries Ltd., Akunoura-cho, Nagasaki-shi Nagasaki-ken, 850-91, Japan","Presently the global warming by CO 2 emission from fossil fuel burning is becoming a serious issue. Especially, coal is the worse fossil fuel, because it emits the largest amount of CO 2 per unit amount of heat generation. There seem to be two ways of reducing substantial CO 2 emission rate of coal; they are, reforming coal to synthesis fuel with less CO 2 emission and removing CO 2 from flue gas of coal fired power station after burning coal. Present paper proposes two nuclear heat application systems which reform coal to methanol and four systems which produce chemical products or gasoline with CO 2 collected from flue gas of coal fired power stations, as future options for reducing CO 2 emission from coal. Advantage and disadvantage of the proposed systems are discussed. © 1997 Elsevier Science Ltd.","CO 2 reuse; Coal reforming; Global warming; Nuclear heat application; Synthesis fuel",,,,,,,"Yasukawa, S., Sato, O., Tadokoro, Y., Kajiyama, T., Shiraki, H., Konta, M., Shimoyamada, Y., (1991) J. Jpn Atomic Energy Soc., 33 (12), pp. 1131-1141; Schroeter, H.J., Kirchhoff, R., Van Heek, K.H., Juentgen, H., Peters, W., (1984) Nucl. Heat Appl., pp. 291-305; Kubiak, H., Schroeter, H.J., Sulimma, A., Van Heek, K.H., (1983) Fuel, 62, pp. 242-245; Schleicher, R.W., Lewis, A.C., (1992) U.S. DOE Rep., 16; Yoshida, K., Kameyama, H., (1980) Chemical Industry; Kameyama, H., Sato, T., Yoshida, K., (1989) Plant and Process, 31 (5), pp. 167-173; Dokiya, M., (1980) Chemical Industry; Imai, Y., Mizuta, S., Nakauchi, H., (1986) Corrosion Engng, 35 (4), pp. 230-240","Hishida, M.; Japan Atom. Ener. Research Institute, Tokai-mura, Naka-gun, Ibaraki-ken 319-11, Japan",,,,,,,,01968904,,ECMAD,,"English","Energy Convers. Manage.",Article,Scopus,2-s2.0-0040569206
